Logographic-type.description: Representing an entire spoken word per character.

annotation: rdfs:comment These can be further subdivided based on other characteristics but these are most commonly used in cognition research and relevant in research into dyslexia
rdfs:comment These can be further subdivided based on other characteristics but these are most commonly used in cognition research and relevant in research into dyslexia

Deep-orthographical-type.description: Not having a one-to-one correspondence between sounds (phonemes) and the letters (graphemes) that represent them.

Shallow-orthographic-type.description: Having a one-to-one correspondence between sounds (phonemes) and the letters (graphemes) that represent them.

Syllabary-type.description: Representing one syllable or mora per character.

Organizational-property.description: Relating to an organization or the action of organizing something.

Collection.description: A tag designating a grouping of items such as in a set or list.

Condition-variable.description: An aspect of the experiment or task that is to be varied during the experiment. Task-conditions are sometimes called independent variables or contrasts.

Control-variable.description: An aspect of the experiment that is fixed throughout the study and usually is explicitly controlled.

Def.description: A HED-specific utility tag used with a defined name to represent the tags associated with that definition.

Def-expand.description: A HED specific utility tag that is grouped with an expanded definition. The child value of the Def-expand is the name of the expanded definition.

Definition.description: A HED-specific utility tag whose child value is the name of the concept and the tag group associated with the tag is an English language explanation of a concept.

Event-context.description: A special HED tag inserted as part of a top-level tag group to contain information about the interrelated conditions under which the event occurs. The event context includes information about other events that are ongoing when this event happens.

Event-stream.description: A special HED tag indicating that this event is a member of an ordered succession of events.

Experimental-intertrial.description: A tag used to indicate a part of the experiment between trials usually where nothing is happening.

placeholder.description: Optional label for the intertrial block.

Experimental-trial.description: Designates a run or execution of an activity, for example, one execution of a script. A tag used to indicate a particular organizational part in the experimental design often containing a stimulus-response pair or stimulus-response-feedback triad.

placeholder.description: Optional label for the trial (often a numerical string).

Indicator-variable.description: An aspect of the experiment or task that is measured as task conditions are varied during the experiment. Experiment indicators are sometimes called dependent variables.

Recording.description: A tag designating the data recording. Recording tags are usually have temporal scope which is the entire recording.

Task.description: An assigned piece of work, usually with a time allotment. A tag used to indicate a linkage the structured activities performed as part of the experiment.

placeholder.description: Optional label for the task block.

Time-block.description: A tag used to indicate a contiguous time block in the experiment during which something is fixed or noted.

placeholder.description: Optional label for the task block.

Sensory-property.description: Relating to sensation or the physical senses.

Sensory-attribute.description: A sensory characteristic associated with another entity.

Auditory-attribute.description: Pertaining to the sense of hearing.

Pitch.description: A perceptual property that allows the user to order sounds on a frequency scale.

Sound-envelope.description: Description of how a sound changes over time.

Sound-envelope-attack.description: The time taken for initial run-up of level from nil to peak usually beginning when the key on a musical instrument is pressed.

Sound-envelope-decay.description: The time taken for the subsequent run down from the attack level to the designated sustain level.

Sound-envelope-release.description: The time taken for the level to decay from the sustain level to zero after the key is released.

Sound-envelope-sustain.description: The time taken for the main sequence of the sound duration, until the key is released.

Sound-volume.description: The sound pressure level (SPL) usually the ratio to a reference signal estimated as the lower bound of hearing.

Timbre.description: The perceived sound quality of a singing voice or musical instrument.

Gustatory-attribute.description: Pertaining to the sense of taste.

Savory.description: Belonging to a taste that is salty or spicy rather than sweet.

Sweet.description: Having or resembling the taste of sugar.

Somatic-attribute.description: Pertaining to the feelings in the body or of the nervous system.

Pain.description: The sensation of discomfort, distress, or agony, resulting from the stimulation of specialized nerve endings.

Stress.description: The negative mental, emotional, and physical reactions that occur when environmental stressors are perceived as exceeding the adaptive capacities of the individual.

Tactile-attribute.description: Pertaining to the sense of touch.

Tactile-temperature.description: Having a feeling of hotness or coldness.

Tactile-vibration.description: Having a feeling of mechanical oscillation.

Vestibular-attribute.description: Pertaining to the sense of balance or body position.

Visual-attribute.description: Pertaining to the sense of sight.

Color.description: The appearance of objects (or light sources) described in terms of perception of their hue and lightness (or brightness) and saturation.

CSS-color.description: One of 140 colors supported by all browsers. For more details such as the color RGB or HEX values,check:https://www.w3schools.com/colors/colors_groups.asp.

Color-shade.description: A slight degree of difference between colors, especially with regard to how light or dark it is or as distinguished from one nearly like it.

Dark-shade.description: A color tone not reflecting much light.

Light-shade.description: A color tone reflecting more light.

Grayscale.description: Using a color map composed of shades of gray, varying from black at the weakest intensity to white at the strongest.

HSV-color.description: A color representation that models how colors appear under light.

HSV-value.description: An attribute of a visual sensation according to which an area appears to emit more or less light.

Hue.description: Attribute of a visual sensation according to which an area appears to be similar to one of the perceived colors.

Saturation.description: Colorfulness of a stimulus relative to its own brightness.

placeholder.description: B value of RGB between 0 and 1.

RGB-color.description: A color from the RGB schema.

placeholder.description: B value of RGB between 0 and 1.
G value of RGB between 0 and 1.
R value of RGB between 0 and 1.

Luminance.description: A quality that exists by virtue of the luminous intensity per unit area projected in a given direction.

Luminance-contrast.description: The difference in luminance in specific portions of a scene or image.

placeholder.description: A non-negative value, usually in the range 0 to 1 or alternative 0 to 100, if representing a percentage.

Opacity.description: A measure of impenetrability to light.

Sensory-presentation.description: The entity has a sensory manifestation.

Auditory-presentation.description: The sense of hearing is used in the presentation to the user.

Loudspeaker-separation.description: The distance between two loudspeakers. Grouped with the Distance tag.

Monophonic.description: Relating to sound transmission, recording, or reproduction involving a single transmission path.

Silent.description: The absence of ambient audible sound or the state of having ceased to produce sounds.

Stereophonic.description: Relating to, or constituting sound reproduction involving the use of separated microphones and two transmission channels to achieve the sound separation of a live hearing.

Gustatory-presentation.description: The sense of taste used in the presentation to the user.

Olfactory-presentation.description: The sense of smell used in the presentation to the user.

Somatic-presentation.description: The nervous system is used in the presentation to the user.

Tactile-presentation.description: The sense of touch used in the presentation to the user.

Vestibular-presentation.description: The sense balance used in the presentation to the user.

Visual-presentation.description: The sense of sight used in the presentation to the user.

2D-view.description: A view showing only two dimensions.

Background-view.description: Parts of the view that are farthest from the viewer and usually the not part of the visual focus.

Bistable-view.description: Something having two stable visual forms that have two distinguishable stable forms as in optical illusions.

Foreground-view.description: Parts of the view that are closest to the viewer and usually the most important part of the visual focus.

Foveal-view.description: Visual presentation directly on the fovea. A view projected on the small depression in the retina containing only cones and where vision is most acute.

Map-view.description: A diagrammatic representation of an area of land or sea showing physical features, cities, roads.

Aerial-view.description: Elevated view of an object from above, with a perspective as though the observer were a bird.

Satellite-view.description: A representation as captured by technology such as a satellite.

Street-view.description: A 360-degrees panoramic view from a position on the ground.

Peripheral-view.description: Indirect vision as it occurs outside the point of fixation.

Task-property.description: Something that pertains to a task.

Task-action-type.description: How an agent action should be interpreted in terms of the task specification.

Appropriate-action.description: An action suitable or proper in the circumstances.

Correct-action.description: An action that was a correct response in the context of the task.

Correction.description: An action offering an improvement to replace a mistake or error.

Done-indication.description: An action that indicates that the participant has completed this step in the task.

Imagined-action.description: Form a mental image or concept of something. This is used to identity something that only happened in the imagination of the participant as in imagined movements in motor imagery paradigms.

Inappropriate-action.description: An action not in keeping with what is correct or proper for the task.

Incorrect-action.description: An action considered wrong or incorrect in the context of the task.

Indeterminate-action.description: An action that cannot be distinguished between two or more possibilities in the current context. This tag might be applied when an outside evaluator or a classification algorithm cannot determine a definitive result.

Miss.description: An action considered to be a failure in the context of the task. For example, if the agent is supposed to try to hit a target and misses.

Near-miss.description: An action barely satisfied the requirements of the task. In a driving experiment for example this could pertain to a narrowly avoided collision or other accident.

Ready-indication.description: An action that indicates that the participant is ready to perform the next step in the task.

Task-attentional-demand.description: Strategy for allocating attention toward goal-relevant information.

Bottom-up-attention.description: Attentional guidance purely by externally driven factors to stimuli that are salient because of their inherent properties relative to the background. Sometimes this is referred to as stimulus driven.

Covert-attention.description: Paying attention without moving the eyes.

Divided-attention.description: Integrating parallel multiple stimuli. Behavior involving responding simultaneously to multiple tasks or multiple task demands.

Focused-attention.description: Responding discretely to specific visual, auditory, or tactile stimuli.

Orienting-attention.description: Directing attention to a target stimulus.

Overt-attention.description: Selectively processing one location over others by moving the eyes to point at that location.

Selective-attention.description: Maintaining a behavioral or cognitive set in the face of distracting or competing stimuli. Ability to pay attention to a limited array of all available sensory information.

Sustained-attention.description: Maintaining a consistent behavioral response during continuous and repetitive activity.

Switched-attention.description: Having to switch attention between two or more modalities of presentation.

Top-down-attention.description: Voluntary allocation of attention to certain features. Sometimes this is referred to goal-oriented attention.

Task-effect-evidence.description: The evidence supporting the conclusion that the event had the specified effect.

Behavioral-evidence.description: An indication or conclusion based on the behavior of an agent.

Computational-evidence.description: A type of evidence in which data are produced, and/or generated, and/or analyzed on a computer.

External-evidence.description: A phenomenon that follows and is caused by some previous phenomenon.

Intended-effect.description: A phenomenon that is intended to follow and be caused by some previous phenomenon.

Task-event-role.description: The purpose of an event with respect to the task.

Cue.description: A signal for an action usually indicating a particular response.

Experimental-stimulus.description: Part of something designed to elicit a response in the experiment.

Feedback.description: An evaluative response to an inquiry, process, event, or activity.

Incidental.description: A sensory or other type of event that is unrelated to the task or experiment.

Instructional.description: Usually associated with a sensory event intended to give instructions to the participant about the task or behavior.

Mishap.description: Unplanned disruption such as an equipment or experiment control abnormality or experimenter error.

Participant-response.description: Something related to a participant actions in performing the task.

Task-activity.description: Something that is part of the overall task or is necessary to the overall experiment but is not directly part of a stimulus-response cycle. Examples would be taking a survey or provided providing a silva sample.

Warning.description: Something that should warn the participant that the parameters of the task have been or are about to be exceeded such as a warning message about getting too close to the shoulder of the road in a driving task.

Background-subtask.description: A part of the task which should be performed in the background as for example inhibiting blinks due to instruction while performing the primary task.

Primary-subtask.description: A part of the task which should be the primary focus of the participant.

Task-stimulus-role.description: The role the stimulus or other type of sensory event, such as feedback, plays in the task.

Distractor.description: A person or thing that distracts or a plausible but incorrect option in a multiple-choice question. In psychological studies this is sometimes referred to as a foil.

Expected.description: Considered likely, probable or anticipated. Something of low information value as in frequent non-targets in an RSVP paradigm.

Extraneous.description: Irrelevant or unrelated to the subject being dealt with.

Go-signal.description: An indicator to proceed with a planned action.

Newly-learned.description: Representing recently acquired information or understanding.

Non-informative.description: Something that is not useful in forming an opinion or judging an outcome.

Non-target.description: Something other than that done or looked for. Also tag Expected if the Non-target is frequent.

Not-meaningful.description: Not having a serious, important, or useful quality or purpose.

Novel.description: Having no previous example or precedent or parallel.

Penalty.description: A disadvantage, loss, or hardship due to some action.

Planned.description: Something that was decided on or arranged in advance.

Priming.description: An implicit memory effect in which exposure to a stimulus influences response to a later stimulus.

Query.description: A sentence of inquiry that asks for a reply.

Reward.description: A positive reinforcement for a desired action, behavior or response.

Stop-signal.description: An indicator that the agent should stop the current activity.

Target.description: Something fixed as a goal, destination, or point of examination.

Threat.description: An indicator that signifies hostility and predicts an increased probability of attack.

Timed.description: Something planned or scheduled to be done at a particular time or lasting for a specified amount of time.

Unplanned.description: Something that has not been planned as part of the task.

Relation.description: Concerns the way in which two or more people or things are connected.

Comparative-relation.description: Something considered in comparison to something else. The first entity is the focus.

Approximately-equal-to.description: (A, (Approximately-equal-to, B)) indicates that A and B have almost the same value. Here A and B could refer to sizes, orders, positions or other quantities.

Equal-to.description: (A, (Equal-to, B)) indicates that the size or order of A is the same as that of B.

Greater-than.description: (A, (Greater-than, B)) indicates that the relative size or order of A is bigger than that of B.

Greater-than-or-equal-to.description: (A, (Greater-than-or-equal-to, B)) indicates that the relative size or order of A is bigger than or the same as that of B.

Less-than.description: (A, (Less-than, B)) indicates that A is smaller than B. Here A and B could refer to sizes, orders, positions or other quantities.

Less-than-or-equal-to.description: (A, (Less-than-or-equal-to, B)) indicates that the relative size or order of A is smaller than or equal to B.

Not-equal-to.description: (A, (Not-equal-to, B)) indicates that the size or order of A is not the same as that of B.

Connective-relation.description: Indicates two entities are related in some way. The first entity is the focus.

Belongs-to.description: (A, (Belongs-to, B)) indicates that A is a member of B.

Connected-to.description: (A, (Connected-to, B)) indicates that A is related to B in some respect, usually through a direct link.

Contained-in.description: (A, (Contained-in, B)) indicates that A is completely inside of B.

Described-by.description: (A, (Described-by, B)) indicates that B provides information about A.

From-to.description: (A, (From-to, B)) indicates a directional relation from A to B. A is considered the source.

Group-of.description: (A, (Group-of, B)) indicates A is a group of items of type B.

Implied-by.description: (A, (Implied-by, B)) indicates B is suggested by A.

Includes.description: (A, (Includes, B)) indicates that A has B as a member or part.

Interacts-with.description: (A, (Interacts-with, B)) indicates A and B interact, possibly reciprocally.

Member-of.description: (A, (Member-of, B)) indicates A is a member of group B.

Part-of.description: (A, (Part-of, B)) indicates A is a part of the whole B.

Performed-by.description: (A, (Performed-by, B)) indicates that the action or procedure A was carried out by agent B.

Performed-using.description: (A, (Performed-using, B)) indicates that the action or procedure A was accomplished using B.

Related-to.description: (A, (Related-to, B)) indicates A has some relationship to B.

Unrelated-to.description: (A, (Unrelated-to, B)) indicates that A is not related to B.For example, A is not related to Task.

Directional-relation.description: A relationship indicating direction of change of one entity relative to another. The first entity is the focus.

Away-from.description: (A, (Away-from, B)) indicates that A is going or has moved away from B. The meaning depends on A and B.

Towards.description: (A, (Towards, B)) indicates that A is going to or has moved to B. The meaning depends on A and B.

Linguistic-relation.description: Related based on a linguistic property to.

Agreement-with.description: Inflectional adjustment to match grammatical category (e.g. case, number, gender) of.

Orthographic-relatedness-to.description: Connected on the basis of writing or spelling.

Orthographic-distance-to.description: Removed in orthographic or written form (e.g. a measure of how far cat is removed from rat in orthography).

Hamming-distance-to.description: The minimum number of substitutions required to change one string into another string of equal length.

Levenshtein-distance-to.description: The minimum number of single-character edits to change into.

Phonological-relatedness-to.description: Connected on the basis of sound.

Phonological-Levenshtein-distance-to.description: The minimum number of single-phoneme edits to change into.

Semantic-relatedness-to.description: Connected on the basis of meaning to.

Synonymous-to.description: Meaning exactly or nearly the same as.

Logical-relation.description: Indicating a logical relationship between entities. The first entity is usually the focus.

And.description: (A, (And, B)) means A and B are both in effect.

Or.description: (A, (Or, B)) means at least one of A and B are in effect.

Spatial-relation.description: Indicating a relationship about position between entities.

Above.description: (A, (Above, B)) means A is in a place or position that is higher than B.

Across-from.description: (A, (Across-from, B)) means A is on the opposite side of something from B.

Adjacent-to.description: (A, (Adjacent-to, B)) indicates that A is next to B in time or space.

Ahead-of.description: (A, (Ahead-of, B)) indicates that A is further forward in time or space in B.

Around.description: (A, (Around, B)) means A is in or near the present place or situation of B.

Behind.description: (A, (Behind, B)) means A is at or to the far side of B, typically so as to be hidden by it.

Below.description: (A, (Below, B)) means A is in a place or position that is lower than the position of B.

Between.description: (A, (Between, (B, C))) means A is in the space or interval separating B and C.

Bilateral-to.description: (A, (Bilateral, B)) means A is on both sides of B or affects both sides of B.

Bottom-edge-of.description: (A, (Bottom-edge-of, B)) means A is on the bottom most part or or near the boundary of B.

Boundary-of.description: (A, (Boundary-of, B)) means A is on or part of the edge or boundary of B.

Center-of.description: (A, (Center-of, B)) means A is at a point or or in an area that is approximately central within B.

Close-to.description: (A, (Close-to, B)) means A is at a small distance from or is located near in space to B.

Far-from.description: (A, (Far-from, B)) means A is at a large distance from or is not located near in space to B.

In-front-of.description: (A, (In-front-of, B)) means A is in a position just ahead or at the front part of B, potentially partially blocking B from view.

Left-edge-of.description: (A, (Left-edge-of, B)) means A is located on the left side of B on or near the boundary of B.

Left-side-of.description: (A, (Left-side-of, B)) means A is located on the left side of B usually as part of B.

Lower-center-of.description: (A, (Lower-center-of, B)) means A is situated on the lower center part of B (due south). This relation is often used to specify qualitative information about screen position.

Lower-left-of.description: (A, (Lower-left-of, B)) means A is situated on the lower left part of B. This relation is often used to specify qualitative information about screen position.

Lower-right-of.description: (A, (Lower-right-of, B)) means A is situated on the lower right part of B. This relation is often used to specify qualitative information about screen position.

Outside-of.description: (A, (Outside-of, B)) means A is located in the space around but not including B.

Over.description: (A, (Over, B)) means A above is above B so as to cover or protect or A extends over the a general area as from a from a vantage point.

Right-edge-of.description: (A, (Right-edge-of, B)) means A is located on the right side of B on or near the boundary of B.

Right-side-of.description: (A, (Right-side-of, B)) means A is located on the right side of B usually as part of B.

To-left-of.description: (A, (To-left-of, B)) means A is located on or directed toward the side to the west of B when B is facing north. This term is used when A is not part of B.

To-right-of.description: (A, (To-right-of, B)) means A is located on or directed toward the side to the east of B when B is facing north. This term is used when A is not part of B.

Top-edge-of.description: (A, (Top-edge-of, B)) means A is on the uppermost part or or near the boundary of B.

Top-of.description: (A, (Top-of, B)) means A is on the uppermost part, side, or surface of B.

Underneath.description: (A, (Underneath, B)) means A is situated directly below and may be concealed by B.

Upper-center-of.description: (A, (Upper-center-of, B)) means A is situated on the upper center part of B (due north). This relation is often used to specify qualitative information about screen position.

Upper-left-of.description: (A, (Upper-left-of, B)) means A is situated on the upper left part of B. This relation is often used to specify qualitative information about screen position.

Upper-right-of.description: (A, (Upper-right-of, B)) means A is situated on the upper right part of B. This relation is often used to specify qualitative information about screen position.

Within.description: (A, (Within, B)) means A is on the inside of or contained in B.

Temporal-relation.description: A relationship that includes a temporal or time-based component.

After.description: (A, (After, B)) means A happens at a time subsequent to a reference time related to B.

Asynchronous-with.description: (A, (Asynchronous-with, B)) means A happens at times not occurring at the same time or having the same period or phase as B.

Before.description: (A, (Before, B)) means A happens at a time earlier in time or order than B.

During.description: (A, (During, B)) means A happens at some point in a given period of time in which B is ongoing.

Synchronous-with.description: (A, (Synchronous-with, B)) means A happens at occurs at the same time or rate as B.

Waiting-for.description: (A, (Waiting-for, B)) means A pauses for something to happen in B.

euro.description: The official currency of a large subset of member countries of the European Union.

point.description: An arbitrary unit of value, usually an integer indicating reward or penalty.

uV.description: Added as a direct unit because it is the default unit.

dB.description: Intensity expressed as ratio to a threshold. May be used for sound intensity.

candela.description: Units used to express light intensity.

cd.description: Units used to express light intensity.

degree Celsius.description: Units are not allowed to have spaces. Use degree-Celsius or oC.

year.description: Years do not have a constant conversion factor to seconds.

currencyUnits.description: Units indicating the worth of something.

dateTimeClass.description: Date-times should conform to ISO8601 date-time format YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss.000000Z (year, month, day, hour (24h), minute, second, optional fractional seconds, and optional UTC time indicator. Any variation on the full form is allowed.

nameClass.description: Value class designating values that have the characteristics of node names. The allowed characters are alphanumeric, hyphen, and underscore.

numericClass.description: Value must be a valid numerical value.

textClass.description: Values that have the characteristics of text such as in descriptions. The text characters include printable characters (32 <= ASCII< 127) excluding comma, square bracket and curly braces as well as non ASCII (ASCII codes > 127).

annotation.description: A annotation link to an item in another ontology or item.

hedId.description: The unique identifier of this element in the HED namespace.

requireChild.description: This tag must have a descendent.

rooted.description: This top-level library schema node should have a parent which is the indicated node in the partnered standard schema.

takesValue.description: This tag is a hashtag placeholder that is expected to be replaced with a user-defined value.

defaultUnits.description: The default units to use if the placeholder has a unit class but the substituted value has no units.

isPartOf.description: This tag is part of the indicated tag -- as in the nose is part of the face.

relatedTag.description: A HED tag that is closely related to this tag. This attribute is used by tagging tools.

suggestedTag.description: A tag that is often associated with this tag. This attribute is used by tagging tools to provide tagging suggestions.

unitClass.description: The unit class that the value of a placeholder node can belong to.

valueClass.description: Type of value taken on by the value of a placeholder node.

allowedCharacter.description: A special character that is allowed in expressing the value of a placeholder of a specified value class. Allowed characters may be listed individual, named individually, or named as a group as specified in Section 2.2 Character sets and restrictions of the HED specification.

conversionFactor.description: The factor to multiply these units or unit modifiers by to convert to default units.

deprecatedFrom.description: The latest schema version in which the element was not deprecated.

extensionAllowed.description: Users can add unlimited levels of child nodes under this tag. This tag is propagated to child nodes except for hashtag placeholders.

inLibrary.description: The named library schema that this schema element is from. This attribute is added by tools when a library schema is merged into its partnered standard schema.

reserved.description: This tag has special meaning and requires special handling by tools.

SIUnit.description: This unit element is an SI unit and can be modified by multiple and sub-multiple names. Note that some units such as byte are designated as SI units although they are not part of the standard.

SIUnitModifier.description: This SI unit modifier represents a multiple or sub-multiple of a base unit rather than a unit symbol.

SIUnitSymbolModifier.description: This SI unit modifier represents a multiple or sub-multiple of a unit symbol rather than a base symbol.

tagGroup.description: This tag can only appear inside a tag group.

topLevelTagGroup.description: This tag (or its descendants) can only appear in a top-level tag group. There are additional tag-specific restrictions on what other tags can appear in the group with this tag.

unique.description: Only one of this tag or its descendants can be used in the event-level HED string.

unitPrefix.description: This unit is a prefix unit (e.g., dollar sign in the currency units).

unitSymbol.description: This tag is an abbreviation or symbol representing a type of unit. Unit symbols represent both the singular and the plural and thus cannot be pluralized.

annotationProperty.description: The value is not inherited by child nodes.

boolRange.description: This schema attribute's value can be true or false. This property was formerly named boolProperty.

elementDomain.description: This schema attribute can apply to any type of element class (i.e., tag, unit, unit class, unit modifier, or value class). This property was formerly named elementProperty.

tagDomain.description: This schema attribute can apply to node (tag-term) elements. This was added so attributes could apply to multiple types of elements. This property was formerly named nodeProperty.

tagRange.description: This schema attribute's value can be a node. This property was formerly named nodeProperty.

numericRange.description: This schema attribute's value can be numeric.

stringRange.description: This schema attribute's value can be a string.

unitClassDomain.description: This schema attribute can apply to unit classes. This property was formerly named unitClassProperty.

unitClassRange.description: This schema attribute's value can be a unit class.

unitModifierDomain.description: This schema attribute can apply to unit modifiers. This property was formerly named unitModifierProperty.

unitDomain.description: This schema attribute can apply to units. This property was formerly named unitProperty.

unitRange.description: This schema attribute's value can be units.

valueClassDomain.description: This schema attribute can apply to value classes. This property was formerly named valueClassProperty.

valueClassRange.description: This schema attribute's value can be a value class.

epilogue: The current prerelease of the schema is primarily centered around written language and current development focuses on adding grammatical aspect characteristics and spoken word characteristics into the vocabulary.
